
Rollup Summary
 

 
:::::::How to enable callouts batch:::::::: 
Implement Database.AllowsCallouts: 
Add this interface to your batch class definition. For example: public class MyBatch implements Database.Batchable<sObject>, Database.AllowsCallouts. 
Perform the callout: 
You can make the callout within the execute() method of your batch class. It's best to perform DML operations after all callouts are complete to avoid hitting the callout limit within the same transaction, as per the developer.salesforce.com documentation. 
Important considerations
Callout limit: 
A single transaction can only make up to 100 callouts. 
Batch size: 
Set your batch size to 100 or lower if each record requires a callout to stay within the limit. 
Error handling: 
Implement robust try-catch blocks to handle potential errors, such as timeouts or non-200 HTTP responses. 
Asynchronous execution: 
Batch Apex is an asynchronous process, which is ideal for long-running operations like callouts because it doesn't block the user interface. 

:::::::Call out from Schedule:::::::
No, you cannot directly make callouts from a Scheduled Apex class, but you can trigger them indirectly by having the Scheduled Apex class launch a Queueable Apex class or a future method which then performs the callout. Alternatively, you can chain Batch Apex jobs, where the Scheduled Apex class initiates the first batch, and a subsequent batch in the finish method or a new scheduled batch makes the callout. 
Why you can't directly make callouts from Scheduled Apex 
•	Pending Operations: 
Salesforce does not allow callouts from Scheduled Apex because callouts are a pending operation, and the system prevents making a callout when other pending operations (like DML statements or asynchronous processes) are present in the same transaction.
•	Transaction Limits: 
A direct callout from a Scheduled Apex class would create a new, separate transaction, which is also restricted by the system.
Workarounds to make callouts from a Scheduled job
1.	Use a Queueable Apex Class:
•	The Scheduled Apex class can call a Queueable Apex class that implements Database.AllowsCallouts to make the external callout. 
•	This keeps the callout in an asynchronous context, avoiding the limitations of Scheduled Apex. 
2.	Use @future Methods:
•	The Scheduled Apex class can invoke a future method, which runs asynchronously and can handle callouts to external web services. 
3.	Chain Batch Apex:
•	The Scheduled Apex class can execute a Batch Apex job. 
•	The finish() method of this batch job can then launch another Batch Apex job or a Queueable class to perform the callout.
Use od external objects
•	The data itself is never physically stored in Salesforce. Instead, the external object acts as a proxy to the external system.
•	External objects are ideal for working with large amounts of data that you cannot or do not want to import into Salesforce. 
•	By accessing data on demand, you avoid consuming Salesforce storage and processing power to store a copy of the data. 
Best Practices integration
•	Use OAuth 2.0 & Named Credentials for authentication
•	Optimize API calls to avoid hitting limits
•	Implement Retry Mechanisms & Error Handling
•	Use Event Monitoring & Debug Logs
•	Keep detailed documentation of the integration, including its purpose, components, and maintenance procedures.
