Q. What is the difference between Whoid and Whatid?
A. WhatId: ID of a related Account, Opportunity, Campaign, Case, or custom object. Labelis Opportunity/Account ID.
WhoId: ID of a related Contact or Lead. If the WhoId refers to a lead, then the WhatId field must be empty. Label is Contact/Lead ID. If Shared Activities is enabled, this is the ID of a related Lead or primary Contact.
Q. Cab we call future method from batch apex?
A. No we can’t call future method from batch apex. If we try to call it will through to “To many future call” error.
 
Q. difference b/w isBlank and isNull?
A.  
ISBLANK	ISNULL
ISBLANK determines if an expression has value or not. If expression contain value then it will return False else it will return true.	ISNULL determines if an expression is null(blank) then return True else expression have vale then it will return False. 
Syntax: ISBLANK(EXPESSION)	ISNULL(EXPESSION)
It check the expression is blank and return true/false	It check the expression is null and return true/false
It supports text fields	Text fields never be null, so using ISNULL for text fields always return false.
For Numeric fields, ISBLANK function only return true if there is no value and not configured to treat blank fields  0’s .	Numeric fields supports.

S NO	Formula function	Formula option	Field type	Result
1	ISBLANK()	Treat blank fields as zeroes 	Text	TRUE
2	ISBLANK()	Treat blank fields as blanks	Text	True    
3	ISBLANK()	Treat blank fields as zeroes	Number	FALSE
4	ISBLANK()	Treat blank fields as blanks	Number	TRUE
5	ISNULL()	Treat blank fields as zeroes	Text	FALSE
6	ISNULL()	Treat blank fields as blanks	Text	FALSE
7	ISNULL()	Treat blank fields as zeroes	Number	FALSE
8	ISNULL()	Treat blank fields as blanks	Number	TRUE


Q. How to create workflow to be executed only for the record update not for the creation.
A. While creating work flow, select evolution criterial as Create and every time edited. And rule criteria with formula not equal to new record(!ISNEW()) then it will not fire for newly created records and it will fire only for update records.

 

Q. In workflow if we have created time-based workflow and trigger added to the queue. What will happen to the trigger if we deactivate the Workflow.
A. Trigger will exist in the queue and action will executed at the specified time.

Q. In workflow if we have created time-based workflow and trigger added to the queue. What will happen to the trigger if we delete the Workflow action.
A. Trigger will exist in Queue but no action performed since the action will be removed from the workflow.

Q. In workflow if we have created time-based workflow and trigger added to the queue. Now Can we delete the work flow?
A. We can’t delete the work flow. If we want delete work flow in 3 ways. 
1) Deactivate workflow and delete action then delete the work flow
2) deactivate the workflow and remove the trigger from queue manually and delete workflow.
3) Make the entry criteria of the record false then trigger will be removed from the queue and  delete the workflow.

Q. how to pass list of records in lightning component to apex class?
A.  Pass the  list of list records as string parameter(Pass your params as string using JSON.stringify function) from Client side controller and convert them in to list of record in Apex using JSON.deserialize.

Ex: Controller
SaveAccessRequest : function(component, event, helper) {
    var ARLIlist = component.get("v.AccessRequestLineItems");
    var action = component.get("c.getSaveRecord");
    var accessreq = component.get("v.AccessRequest");
var ARLIlistAsString = JSON.stringify(ARLIlist);
var accessreqAsString = JSON.stringify(accessreq);
    action.setParams({"ARAsString":accessreqAsString,
                     "ARLIAsString":ARLIlistAsString});
    $A.enqueueAction(action);
}

Apex code:

@AuraEnabled
public static void getSaveRecord(String ARAsString, String ARLIAsString){

Access_Request__c AR = JSON.deserialize(ARAsString, Access_Request__c.class);
List<Access_Request_Line_Item__c> ARLI = JSON.deserialize(ARLIAsString, List<Access_Request_Line_Item__c>.class);
    Insert AR;
    system.debug('====>'+ARLI);
    for(Integer i=0; i<ARLI.size(); i++){
        ARLI[i].Access_Request_ID__c = AR.id;
    }
    Insert ARLI;
    system.debug('====>'+ARLI[0].id);

}


	

QA:  Workflow and Trigger both are automated then why your going with Trigger?
Ans:  
o	Workflow will be executed  after insert and after update but where as in Triggers we have Before insert, Before update, before delete, after insert, after update, after delete and after undelete. 
o	Workflow can perform only update on the record on which we are running workflow rule but in Trigger we can perform any DML  operation on any object. 
o	Through work flow we can’t create a new record but in trigger we can perform all DML operations.
Q: Process builder and Trigger both are automated then why your going with Trigger?
Ans:  
o	Process builder will be executed  after insert and after update but where as in Triggers we have Before insert, Before update, before delete, after insert, after update, after delete and after undelete. 
o	Process Builder cannot handle delete and undelete DML. Whereas Apex triggers can handle all DML operations.
o	An error reported in Process Builder is more generic which makes it difficult to find the origin of the error. With Apex triggers, exception handling can be made more specific.
o	It is all or none in case of Process Builder failure. But with Apex triggers partial success is possible.
o	Whenever a particular use case is not possible using Process Builder, consider using Apex triggers. For example, consider the below use case:-

A custom field on a Parent object which is based on the field related to the max (roll up) among the child records. Since roll-up functionality involves insert, update, delete and undelete operations, using an Apex trigger is the best option in this scenario.
