A.  The possible mistakes are,
o	The apex class may not be used @Auraenabled for the method which is calling from JS Controller 
o	Not perform the $A.enqueaction(Action)
o	Passing the incorrect parameters
Q. How to handle error in Apex for Lightning components in try-catch block?
 A.  After calling the method from JS controller normally error messages will be handle with Setcallback (this, function(response)). Throw an AuraHandledException in the catch block. This allows you to provide a custom user-friendly error message.The AuraHandledException is sent back to the client with your custom message, Now handled this custom message in Setcallback() method.

// Best practice: user-friendly error message provided by an AuraHandledException
@AuraEnabled
public static void triggerBasicAuraHandledError() {
    try {
        integer a = 1 / 0; // Division by zero causes exception
    }
    catch (Exception e) {
        // "Convert" the exception into an AuraHandledException
        throw new AuraHandledException('Darn it! Something went wrong: '
            + e.getMessage());    
    }
}

In JS controller , Byusing below code we can display to the Page.
var errorMsg = action.getError()[0].message;
                console.log(errorMsg);

